<item>
  <title>Test post: Euler-Lagrange’s equation in simple pendulum</title>
  <dc:creator>Yijia Zhao</dc:creator>
  <link>https://blog.yijialog.org/posts/1/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 






<section id="defination" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="defination">Defination</h2>
<p>Here is the <strong>Euler-Lagrange’s equation</strong>:</p>
<p><span id="eq-label"><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A%5Cfrac%7B%5Cmathrm%7Bd%7D%7D%7B%5Cmathrm%7Bd%7Dt%7D(%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7B%5Cmathcal%7BL%7D%7D%7D%7B%5Cpartial%7B%5Cdot%7Bq_i%7D%7D%7D)=%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpartial%7B%5Cmathcal%7BL%7D%7D%7D%7B%5Cpartial%7Bq_i%7D%7D%0A%5Ctag%7B1%7D"></span></p>
<p>Where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Cmathcal%7BL%7D"> is the <strong>Lagrangian</strong>, defined as <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?T-V">.<br>
In <strong>Mathematica</strong>, we can compute it directly by calling the <code>VariationalMethods</code> package:</p>
<pre><code>Needs["VariationalMethods`"]
L = T - V
EulerEquations[L, {q1[t], q2[t]}, t]</code></pre>
<hr>
</section>
